pouch boundary-line patch 0016 - AF_INET sockets over /net (net-5)

NET-DESIGN.md section 7 (binds D-net-2, closes W4-F2). The kernel has NO
socket syscalls by commitment (ARCH 11.5; NOVEL #1). Linux/pouch binaries
that call socket()/connect()/bind()/listen()/accept()/send()/recv()/
getsockname()/getpeername()/setsockopt() over AF_INET are served by this
boundary-line patch, which translates each to operations on netd's /net 9P
files -- the Genode socket_fs-in-libc model. NO new kernel surface: the
translation uses only SYS_open / SYS_read / SYS_write / SYS_close, all
already seamed by 0001/0006. (syscall.h.in is intentionally unchanged.)

This STACKS on 0006-pouch-sockets.patch (the AF_UNIX-over-/srv layer): the
musl socket calls are single functions 0006 already overrides, so net-5
extends each with a family dispatch rather than adding parallel files. A
slot carries family POUCH_SOCK_FAM_UNIX (the 0006 /srv path, family 0 so a
zeroed slot defaults to it) or POUCH_SOCK_FAM_INET (the /net path); the two
never mix. The blocking subset only -- non-blocking I/O + poll()/select()
over /net fds need the dev9p.poll readiness bridge (net-6), so SOCK_NONBLOCK
returns EOPNOTSUPP (P-3: no silently-wrong POSIX).

The translation table (NET-DESIGN.md section 7; ground truth = netd's
server.rs):
  socket(AF_INET, SOCK_STREAM|DGRAM)  open("/net/{tcp,udp}/clone") -- the
                                      Plan 9 connection factory (3.2/4);
                                      the opened fid is the new conn's ctl,
                                      reading it yields N. ctl + N held in
                                      the slot for its lifetime.
  connect(fd, sockaddr_in)            write "connect a.b.c.d!port" to ctl,
                                      then open(/net/<proto>/N/data) (blocks
                                      to ESTABLISHED for TCP). data fd ->
                                      slot kernel_fd (the I/O target).
  bind(fd, sockaddr_in)               stash the local addr pouch-side; netd
                                      has no `bind` ctl verb (NET-DESIGN 3.3
                                      design, unwired). listen() announces
                                      lport; getsockname() reports it.
  listen(fd, backlog)                 write "announce *!port" (or
                                      "announce a.b.c.d!port") to ctl. TCP
                                      only; backlog is netd's (net-3a).
  accept(fd)                          open(/net/tcp/N/listen) (blocks) ->
                                      the new conn M's ctl; read M; open
                                      M/data; mint a fresh tagged slot for
                                      it. Peer addr from M/remote. The
                                      listener slot stays LISTENING.
  send/recv, read/write               the 0006 dispatch is unchanged: a
                                      tagged fd routes through the slot's
                                      kernel_fd (the data fd) to SYS_write/
                                      SYS_read.
  getsockname/getpeername             read /net/<proto>/N/local | /remote
                                      (or, for getsockname pre-connect, the
                                      bind()-stashed addr).
  setsockopt                          SO_REUSEADDR/SO_REUSEPORT/TCP_NODELAY
                                      -> benign no-op (netd already
                                      satisfies the semantic); the rest ->
                                      ENOPROTOOPT (the keepalive/ttl/tos ctl
                                      verbs are a documented net-5 seam).
  getsockopt                          SO_ERROR (0; blocking) / SO_TYPE; the
                                      rest -> ENOPROTOOPT.
  close                               the 0006 path also closes the held
                                      ctl fd for a FAM_INET slot.

Invariants (NET-DESIGN.md section 15.1 -- composes existing section-28
invariants, adds none): I-1/I-23/I-28 (a Proc reaches only the /net its
territory grants -- the namespace firewall, section 8); I-5 (netd owns the
NIC; pouch never touches hardware). The slot table's thread-safety is 0006's
(g_lock around every structural change; pthread peers share it). A FAM_INET
slot holds two kernel fds -- ctl (lifetime) + data (post-connect) -- both
closed at close().

